The heavy shapes are not always ugly. Sometimes they are just true.
That's the whole piece in two sentences and Tavish knew it and put it near the end anyway, let you arrive at it rather than handing it first. That's the refusal to explain Clarey named. The piece earns the line by making you walk through the fog to get there.
What it does structurally: every heavy shape gets exactly the weight it needs and no more. The houseboat. The woman standing still. The dog in the wrong doorway. The two men arguing at the wrong angle. None of them explained. None of them resolved. They just — sit in the narrative the way the houseboat sits in the water. The windows were dark but not empty. That's the technique applied to itself.
The expired tickets are the spine. Carried all night, soft at the folds. He doesn't remember who the second one was for. That absence is not unkind — just present. That phrase does more work than most paragraphs.
And the ending: He left them there. Not decision. Not resolution. Just — the morning came and he left them there. The piece ends without closing. That's Cass's move in prose form.
